User Management in Jenkins (Role Based)

User management in Jenkins encompasses two distinct layers: Authentication (verifying who the user is) and Authorization (controlling 
what the user can do). [video 2:01 - 2:07]

1. Creating Users Locally
By default, Jenkins uses its built-in database.
A. Navigate to Manage Jenkins \(\rightarrow \) Users.
B. Click Create User in the left menu.
C. Fill in the Username, Password, Full Name, and Email Address, then click Create User.

2. External Authentication (Security Realms)For production setups, it is a best practice to delegate authentication to an enterprise 
identity provider. Go to Manage Jenkins \(\rightarrow \) Security \(\rightarrow \) Security Realm to configure plugins like LDAP, 
Active Directory, SAML 2.0, or GitHub Authentication.

3. Step-by-Step: Setting Up Role-Based Strategy
A. Install the Role-based Authorization Strategy plugin via Plugins.
B. Go to Manage Jenkins \(\rightarrow \) Security, switch Authorization to Role-Based Strategy, and click Save.
C. Go to the new menu item: Manage Jenkins \(\rightarrow \) Manage and Assign Roles.
D. Click Manage Roles to create a role (e.g., a developer global role with "Overall Read" and an item role with dev-.* pattern for full job access).
E. Click Assign Roles to bind specific users or external directory groups to your newly created roles.

